Version Date: 2013-06-25Version Text: 2013-06-25Version Date: 2013-06-25Version Text: 2013-06-25 Subject: null  Type: null  Notes: Released Methodological Resources documentation and updated xml file to include variable groupings.;Version Date: 2006-12-07Version Text: 2006-12-07 Subject: null  Type: null  Notes: On October 4, 2006, the data producer resupplied the data file and codebook documentation. In this new data file, 21 variables were m
odified, 9 variables were dropped, and 8 new variables were added. Some of these changes were to correct for data errors, but most of these changes were done to provide consistency with the 2004 NSDUH study. Of these changes, the most important change to note is that two study design variables (VEREP and VESTR) were revised to provide consistency with the 2004 study, which collapsed the strata in order to maximize the number of people in each replicate.;Version Date: 2004-03-30Version Text: 2004-03-30 Subject: null  Type: null  Notes: Coding errors were corrected in the following variables: IILSDRC, II2LSDRC, IIPCPRC, II2PCPRC, IIMTHRC, II2MTHRC, NRCH17_2, MTHYR, and MTHMON.;Version Date: 2003-03-11Version Text: 2003-03-11 Subject: null  Type: null  Notes: An errata file was added to the data collection.; Subject: null  Type: null  Notes: LRECL with SAS, SPSS, and Stata setup files, SAS transport (XPORT) file, SPSS portable file, and Stata system file;Subject: Study Level Error Note, Notes: Users are advised to review the errata file prior to conducting any analyses.;Subject: Study Level Error Note, Notes: Data were collected and prepared for release by Research Triangle Institute, Research Triangle Park, NC.;Subject: Study Level Error Note, Notes: The National Household Survey on Drug Abuse survey administration and sample design changed with the implementation of the 1999 survey. Since 1999, the survey sample has employed a 50-State design with an independent, multistage area probability sample for each of the 50 States and the District of Columbia. Therefore, estimates produced from the 1999, 2000, and 2001 surveys are not comparable to those produced from the 1998 and earlier surveys.;Subject: Study Level Error Note, Notes: For selected variables, statistical imputation was performed following logical inference to replace missing responses. These variables are identified in the codebook as "...LOGICALLY ASSIGNED" for the logical procedure, or by the designation "IMPUTATION-REVISED" in the variable label when the statistical procedure was also performed. The names of statistically imputed variables begin with the letters "IR". For each imputation-revised variable there is a corresponding imputation indicator variable that indicates whether a case's value on the variable resulted from an interview response or was imputed. Missing values for some demographic variables were imputed by the unweighted hot-deck technique used in previous NHSDAs. Beginning in 1999, imputation of missing values for many other variables was accomplished using predictive mean neighborhoods (PMN), a new procedure developed specifically for the NHSDA. Both the hot-deck and PMN imputation procedures are described in the codebook.;Subject: Study Level Error Note, Notes: To protect the privacy of respondents, all variables that could be used to identify individuals have been encryp
ted or collapsed in the public use file. To further ensure respondent confidentiality, the data producer used data substitution and deletion of state identifiers and a subsample of records in the creation of the public use file.;Subject: Study Level Error Note, Notes: Previously published estimates may not be exactly reproducible from the variables in the public use file due to the disclosure protection procedures that were implemented.;Subject: Study Level Error Note, Notes: The data definition and dictionary files for Stata are designed to be compatible with StataSE, Version 8. This is a large data file requiring that approximately 250 megabytes of Random Access Memory be allocated to Stata. Operations within Stata, including conversion of the ASCII data to Stata format, are likely to be slow. Analysts may wish to download subsets of data from the SAMHDA Data Analysis System (DAS) for use with Stata.; Subject: null  Type: null  Notes: Stata system file(s), SPSS portable file(s), Data file(s), SAS transport - XPORT engine file(s), and electronic documentation.;
